# LangGraph Project

A LangGraph-based agent system with production-ready architecture.

## Quick Start

\`\`\`bash
# Install dependencies
make setup

# Start development server
make dev

# Run tests
make test
\`\`\`

## Project Structure

- \`agents/default/\` - Main agent implementation
  - \`src/graphs/\` - Graph definitions and subgraphs
    - \`agent-feedback/\` - AI agent feedback loops
    - \`human-feedback/\` - Human-in-the-loop workflows
    - \`coordinator/\` - Multi-agent coordination
    - \`logger/\` - Logging and observability
  - \`src/nodes/\` - Individual workflow nodes
  - \`src/skills/\` - Reusable skills and capabilities
  - \`src/config/\` - Configuration management
- \`shared/\` - Shared utilities across agents
- \`ui/\` - User interface implementations

## Environment Variables

Copy \`agents/default/.env.example\` to \`agents/default/.env\` and configure:

### Cloud Providers

- \`LANGSMITH_API_KEY\` - For observability (optional)
- \`OPENAI_API_KEY\` or \`ANTHROPIC_API_KEY\` - Model provider

### LM Studio (Local Models)

For local development with [LM Studio](https://lmstudio.ai/):

1. Start LM Studio and load a model
2. Configure in \`.env\`:
   - \`LM_STUDIO_BASE_URL=http://localhost:1234/v1\`
   - \`LM_STUDIO_API_KEY=lm-studio\` (any value works)
   - \`LM_STUDIO_MODEL_NAME=local-model\` (or your model name)
3. Copy \`src/graphs/main_graph_lmstudio.py\` to \`src/graphs/main.py\`
4. Update \`langgraph.json\` if needed

Example LM Studio graph is provided in \`src/graphs/main_graph_lmstudio.py\`

## Semantic Versioning

This project uses [semantic-release](https://github.com/semantic-release/semantic-release) for automated changelog generation.

Commit message format:
- \`feat: description\` - New feature (minor version)
- \`fix: description\` - Bug fix (patch version)
- \`docs: description\` - Documentation only
- \`chore: description\` - Maintenance tasks

The CHANGELOG.md is automatically updated on push to main.